                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.42793/9–2444: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-24T13:00:00+07:00"
                            >September 24, 1944—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 25—9:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1606. Embassy’s 1450, August 24, noon. Central News report September 20 that the
                    ban on Chinese students going abroad for study has been completely lifted
                    confirmed by Ministry of Education. Those going at own expense may leave as soon
                    as they have completed certain procedure which though unspecified is not
                    expected to be onerous or obstructive. Examinations for Government scholarships
                    are announced by Central News to take place first week of December in 7 cities
                    for selection of 181 students for advanced study in the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
